Problem 1¶

Mechanical systems are always vibrating when operating. So, vibration analysis is one of the most popular and conventional ways to diagnose the mechanical system. In this problem, we are going to use the CNN-RNN algorithm to identify abnormality of a bearing.

  • Information: signal, label

  • Sampling rate: 12,800 Hz

  • The data is stored in the form of a dictionary for 10 classes.

Problem 2¶

GAN(Generative Adversrial Network) model is generative model creating new data instances that resemble training data. In this problem, we will perform anomaly detection using the GAN and autoencoder model. Let's assume that there are two classes, normal and abnormal. GAN and autoencoder model is trained by only normal data. The autoencoder model creates fake normal data that is similar to the real normal data. As a result, even if the input data is abnormal, the autoencoder model generates a normal data that is the most similar input data. Finally, we classify the data as abnormal using the anomaly score. You don't need to fully understand in this step. In the following problems, you will be given a detail decription.

Dataset Descrption¶

In this problem, we use MNIST dataset which contain handwritten digits. Digit 1 is used as normal data and other digits are used as abnormal data. As explained above, we use only digit 1 image as normal data when training the model.
You can download the data in .npy format.

2.6 Training Encoder Model [10pt]¶

As shown in the below figure, an encoder is trained by two loss terms, $L_A, L_B$.
$L_A$ part follows a standard autoencoder configuration. We minimize the MSE residual loss of input images x and reconstructed images G(E(x)):

$$L_A = \frac{1}{n}\cdot||x - G(E(x))||^2$$

$L_B$ is the loss function for discriminator guided encoder training.

$$L_B = \frac{1}{n}\cdot||f(x) - f(G(E(x)))||^2$$

where $f(\cdot)$ indicate intermediate layer feature of discriminator. For information on where to extract the discriminator feature, refer to the discriminator figure above (problem 2.2.2).
$L_{total}$ is defined as the sum of $L_A$ and $L_B$.

$$L_{total} = \frac{1}{n}\cdot||x - G(E(x))||^2 + \frac{1}{n}\cdot||f(x) - f(G(E(x)))||^2$$

When training the encoder model, the parameters of the GAN model must be fixed.
